    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9dc4e867-68bc-462e-af77-77dcef1ee6c9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 2-year-old girl brought to clinic by her mother after two days of worsening fever, cough, and fast breathing. She appears tired and clingy, sitting limp in her caregiver’s arms and becoming fussy when examined. Her cheeks are flushed, her nose is mildly congested, and she has a frequent wet-sounding cough. Between coughing spells she breathes more quickly than expected for age, with mild chest wall retractions and reduced interest in play.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is usually active, curious, and sociable. She attends daycare three days a week, where several children recently had colds. She enjoys picture books, toy animals, and following her older cousin around the house. Over the last 24 hours she has eaten less than usual, taken only small sips of fluids, and had fitful sleep because of cough and fever.\n\nShe lives with both parents in a small apartment and is up to date on routine childhood care. There is no smoking inside the home, though her father smokes outside occasionally. Her parents describe her as generally healthy with normal growth and development. They became concerned when she developed persistent fever, noisy breathing during sleep, and seemed less interactive than usual."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:8c94c512-5c2b-4837-ab03-7c0b6f9b2bbc",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no chronic medical conditions and no prior history of asthma, congenital heart disease, or recurrent lung infections. She was born at term without neonatal complications and has had no prior hospitalizations. Her immunizations are reported as current for age. Over the past week, she had rhinorrhea after a daycare exposure, followed by fever and worsening cough.\n\nHer caregivers report decreased appetite, reduced oral intake, and fewer wet diapers today, suggesting mild dehydration risk. There is occasional secondhand smoke exposure from a parent who smokes outdoors. No known aspiration event, seizure history, or immunodeficiency is reported. She has not recently traveled and has no known tuberculosis exposure."
          }
        ]
      }
